hands_on_practices.solution:
1. The first-order displacement amplitude $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s$ is related to the velocity amplitude $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{v}}_s$ by the harmonic time dependence $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{v}}_s=-i\omega\,\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s$. Thus,
$$\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s=\frac{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{v}}_s}{-i\omega}
=\frac{i}{\omega}\frac{i q E_0(x)}{m_s(\omega-\Omega_s)}(\hat{x}+i\hat{y})
=-\frac{qE_0(x)}{m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}(\hat{x}+i\hat{y})\,. $$

2. The ponderomotive force is $\mathbf{F}_{p,s}=\frac12\Re\bigl[q(\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s^*\!\cdot\nabla)\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}_1\bigr]$, with $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}_1=E_0(x)(\hat{x}+i\hat{y})$. The complex conjugate of the displacement is $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s^* = -\frac{qE_0(x)}{m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}(\hat{x}-i\hat{y})$.

3. Since the field amplitude $E_0(x)$ only varies in $x$, the gradient operator becomes $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s^*\!\cdot\nabla = \mathcal{r}_{s,x}^* \frac{\partial}{\partial x}$. Applying this gives:
$$(\boldsymbol{\mathcal{r}}_s^*\!\cdot\nabla)\boldsymbol{\mathcal{E}}_1
=\mathcal{r}_{s,x}^*\,\frac{dE_0}{dx}(\hat{x}+i\hat{y})
=-\frac{qE_0}{m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}\frac{dE_0}{dx}(\hat{x}+i\hat{y})\,. $$

4. Substituting this into the force expression:
$$\mathbf{F}_{p,s}
=\frac12\Re\left[-\frac{q^2E_0}{m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}\frac{dE_0}{dx}(\hat{x}+i\hat{y})\right]
=-\frac{q^2}{2m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}
E_0\frac{dE_0}{dx}\,\hat{x}
=-\frac{q^2}{4m_s\,\omega(\omega-\Omega_s)}\frac{d}{dx}(E_0^2)\,\hat{x}\,.
$$

5. Taking the magnitudes and forming the ratio $R = |\mathbf{F}_{p,A}|/|\mathbf{F}_{p,B}|$:
$$R
=\frac{\displaystyle\frac{q^2}{4m_A\,|\omega(\omega-\Omega_A)|}}
{\displaystyle\frac{q^2}{4m_B\,|\omega(\omega-\Omega_B)|}}
=\frac{m_B}{m_A}\frac{|\omega-\Omega_B|}{|\omega-\Omega_A|}
=\alpha\frac{|\omega-\Omega_B|}{|\omega-\Omega_A|}\,. $$

6. We are given $\Omega_B=\Omega_A/\alpha$ and $\omega=\sqrt{\Omega_A\Omega_B}=\Omega_A/\sqrt\alpha$. The frequency differences are:
$$\omega-\Omega_A=\Omega_A\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt\alpha}-1\right) = -\Omega_A\frac{\sqrt\alpha-1}{\sqrt\alpha}$$
$$\omega-\Omega_B=\Omega_A\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt\alpha}-\frac{1}{\alpha}\right)
=\frac{\Omega_A}{\alpha}(\sqrt\alpha-1)\,.$$
Since $\alpha > 1$, both factors are non-zero. The ratio of their magnitudes is:
$$\frac{|\omega-\Omega_B|}{|\omega-\Omega_A|}
=\frac{\frac{\Omega_A}{\alpha}(\sqrt\alpha-1)}{\Omega_A\frac{\sqrt\alpha-1}{\sqrt\alpha}}
=\frac{1/\alpha}{1/\sqrt\alpha}
=\frac{1}{\sqrt\alpha}\,. $$

7. Finally, substituting this back into the expression for $R$:
$$R=\alpha\cdot\frac1{\sqrt\alpha}=\sqrt\alpha\,. $$
